 <H1>Transaction: An Execution of a DB Program</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI><H2>Key concept is transaction, which is an atomic sequence of database actions (reads/writes).
</H2>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>Each transaction, executed completely, must leave the DB in a consistent state if DB is consistent when the transaction begins.
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Users can specify some simple integrity constraints on the data, and the DBMS will enforce these constraints.
<LI>Beyond this, the DBMS does not really understand the semantics of the data.  (e.g., it does not understand how the interest on a bank account is computed).
<LI>Thus, ensuring that a transaction (run alone) preserves consistency is ultimately the user’s responsibility!</UL></UL></P>
